    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_884422495" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/884422495" />
    <a title="Stepheny" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7091879-stepheny"><img alt="Stepheny" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1567725280p2/7091879.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/884422495?book_show_action=true">Jan 30, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stepheny" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stepheny" href="/user/show/7091879-stepheny">Stepheny</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/18803062-love-letters-to-the-dead">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7091879-stepheny?shelf=ya">ya</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer884422495" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1116518591656175452"><br/>4.5<br/><br/>You all are well aware by now that I am completely and helplessly obsessed with YA books. I’ll read just about anything in that genre. Literally. I can’t get enough of it. I don’t know if I never grew up from my own teenage years, or if I felt that my teenage years weren&apos;t what they were supposed to be, or if I just have some weird fascination with teenagers. What I do know is that I can’t say no to YA novels.<br/><br/>Love Letters to the Dead was brought to my attention by one of those stupid fake Dea</span>
  <span id="freeText1116518591656175452" style="display:none"><br />4.5<br /><br />You all are well aware by now that I am completely and helplessly obsessed with YA books. I’ll read just about anything in that genre. Literally. I can’t get enough of it. I don’t know if I never grew up from my own teenage years, or if I felt that my teenage years weren't what they were supposed to be, or if I just have some weird fascination with teenagers. What I do know is that I can’t say no to YA novels.<br /><br />Love Letters to the Dead was brought to my attention by one of those stupid fake Dear John letters from other authors you get in your email once in a while. This one happened to come from the author of Perks of Being a Wallflower(fat chance of me trying to type out THAT guy’s last name. Ha!). He said if I loved Perks so much why didn’t I marry it. Just kidding, he did say that if I loved Perks, I would also love this new book. <br /><br />And wouldn't you know it was a kindle daily deal and I snagged it for $1.99…. and it sat on my kindle for almost a year before I got around to it. <br /><br />Once I picked it up, I had a hard time putting it down. <br /><br />Luckily for me, I had just given birth to a sweet baby boy who had me up all hours of the night… and his every movement or sound prevented me from falling asleep in the first place, so I got through this one pretty damn quickly!<br /><br />Laurel is about to start high school at a new school. Her sister died and it was tragic. But Laurel isn't about to give up any details about that night. At least not at first. <br /><br />The story is told in a series of letters written to dead celebrities. It was an English assignment: write a letter to a dead person who interests you. Laurel chooses Kurt Cobain-nice choice, Laurel. But she doesn't stop there. She goes on to write to Jim Morrison, Amy Winehouse, Judy Garland and other people who have impacted her in some way or another. But most of these people are people who were loved by her sister May. <br /><br />This is a story of self-discovery. It’s a coming of age tale. It’s about heartbreak and lonliness. It’s about buried secrets that become too much to bear. It’s about substance abuse. It’s about depression. It’s about all of the things that high-school aged kids go through on a regular fucking basis. Now maybe your high school days were great and you were the captain of the school <s> Quidditch</s> football team, but not everyone had that experience. A lot, I’d even say a majority, of kids fall more in line with Laurel’s story.<br /><br /><br />I really loved Laurel. I wanted to hang out and listen to angsty grunge music and talk about how people just don’t. fucking. get. it. I am a HUGE fan of 90’s grunge and so this might be another reason this book resonated so deeply with me. Kurt Cobain foreverrrrr. &lt;3 <br /><br />Anyway, this story broke my heart. But I loved it. I loved every word. I loved it all. I just wish it was a little longer in some areas and a little briefer in others. I wish that I had come out with my buried secret all those years ago, but I didn’t. The hard part, as Laurel finds out, is talking to people you love about the pain you are going through. Sometimes it’s easier to swallow it down and bury it deep within you, allowing the weight of it to drag you down day in and day out than it is to tell a loved one- I’m hurting. <br /><br />Our instinct to protect the ones we love combined with our desire to not be pitied results in buried secrets like Laurel’s. How we cope with it is different for all of us. Laurel chose to express it through writing. Venting to people she knew she’d never meet helped coax that secret out eventually and watching her progress was a wonderful experience. <br /><br />This book is everything I love about YA. And about coming-of-age. <br /><br />Thank you, Laurel. You’ve helped me in ways you can’t imagine.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1116518591656175452" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


