<div id="review_919502609" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/919502609" />
    <a title="Sarah Churchill" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18321322-sarah-churchill"><img alt="Sarah Churchill" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1628018504p2/18321322.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/919502609?book_show_action=true">Apr 24, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sarah Churchill" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sarah Churchill" href="/user/show/18321322-sarah-churchill">Sarah Churchill</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781471402883" href="/book/show/20703051-love-letters-to-the-dead">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18321322-sarah-churchill?shelf=books-i-own">books-i-own</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18321322-sarah-churchill?shelf=received-for-review">received-for-review</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer919502609" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6331834959619449430">Wow. I don&apos;t know where to start... <br/><br/>The only reason this didn&apos;t get 5 stars from me is because I found it a teensy bit slow to begin with, and the main character Laurel wasn&apos;t particularly likeable. That&apos;s entirely on purpose, I know, but I just didn&apos;t buy into her story right away. Once the layers started to peel away though - and this book is FULL of layers, like onions and Shrek - it became a deep and powerful masterpiece.<br/><br/>The secrets that have been haunting Laurel are eventually revealed, and</span>
  <span id="freeText6331834959619449430" style="display:none">Wow. I don't know where to start... <br /><br />The only reason this didn't get 5 stars from me is because I found it a teensy bit slow to begin with, and the main character Laurel wasn't particularly likeable. That's entirely on purpose, I know, but I just didn't buy into her story right away. Once the layers started to peel away though - and this book is FULL of layers, like onions and Shrek - it became a deep and powerful masterpiece.<br /><br />The secrets that have been haunting Laurel are eventually revealed, and although it wasn't really surprising (and dare I say it, almost predictable) it didn't matter because the writing was fantastic. So much depth. Like reading poetry. <br /><br />I also loved that we saw the supporting characters grow so much during the course of the book, and this is as much their story as it is Laurel's. Being written as a collection of letters brought an extra feeling of sincerity and soul-bearing honesty that a standard narrative can't achieve, especially letters to the dead. They can remain unread, and forever a secret, so Laurel can be more honest in writing to these dead 'role models' than she often is with herself.<br /><br />I could probably write an entire essay, but I won't. Contemporary lovers out there... this. Get this.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6331834959619449430" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


