<div id="review_1376694986" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1376694986" />
    <a title="India" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/38467984-india"><img alt="India" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1476996171p2/38467984.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1376694986?book_show_action=true">Aug 28, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="India" class="user" itemprop="url" name="India" href="/user/show/38467984-india">India</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38467984-india?shelf=own-a-copy">own-a-copy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38467984-india?shelf=2016">2016</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38467984-india?shelf=i-wish-i-knew-these-people">i-wish-i-knew-these-people</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38467984-india?shelf=beautiful-conclusions">beautiful-conclusions</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38467984-india?shelf=i-feel-bad-for-these-characters">i-feel-bad-for-these-characters</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38467984-india?shelf=gorgeous-cover">gorgeous-cover</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38467984-india?shelf=great-mc">great-mc</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38467984-india?shelf=happy-tears">happy-tears</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38467984-india?shelf=quick-reads">quick-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38467984-india?shelf=who-ends-up-together">who-ends-up-together</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1376694986" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16871417291164935484"><b>Rating:</b><br/><br/>4 stars. <i>Love Letters to the Dead </i> is an amazing book, but I made the mistake of going into it with really high expectations, and that made it seem like it wasn&apos;t as good as it could have been.<br/><br/>I hate when I do that.<br/><br/><blockquote>Maybe when we can tell the stories, however bad they are, we don&apos;t belong to them anymore. They become ours. And maybe what growing up really means is knowing that you don&apos;t have to just be a character, going whichever way the story says. It&apos;s knowing that you could be the auth</blockquote></span>
  <span id="freeText16871417291164935484" style="display:none"><b>Rating:</b><br /><br />4 stars. <i>Love Letters to the Dead </i> is an amazing book, but I made the mistake of going into it with really high expectations, and that made it seem like it wasn't as good as it could have been.<br /><br />I hate when I do that.<br /><br /><blockquote>Maybe when we can tell the stories, however bad they are, we don't belong to them anymore. They become ours. And maybe what growing up really means is knowing that you don't have to just be a character, going whichever way the story says. It's knowing that you could be the author instead.</blockquote><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><b>Plot:</b><br /><br /><i>Summary </i><br /><br />9th grader Laurel has lost her sister, her mother, and her hope.<br /><br />Her older sister, May, her role model, her best friend, her companion, died in an accident a few months ago.<br /><br />Her parents divorced just before that, and her mom fled to California after.<br /><br />She has no one left except her Dad - who shuts himself away a lot - and her Aunt Amy - who is too strict for Laurel's liking.<br /><br />That is, until she finds what she needed in those who have also left.<br /><br />Kurt Cobain, Judy Garland, Jim Morrison, Janis Joplin, Amelia Earhart, and so many more. Laurel writes to them, first to fulfill an English assignment, but then because she just really needs someone to talk to.<br /><br />Through her letters, we see the next year through her eyes. She meets new friends, falls in love, learns to appreciate life, and accepts what she never thought she could.<br /><br /><br /><i>Commentary </i><br /><br />Beautiful, beautiful, beautiful. I don't really know what I expected out of this book when I dove in. I knew it would be amazing, but I was not aware that I would become so enraptured in the life of a girl just like so many. But at the same time, she really is so different.<br /><br />I, personally, have not lost anyone so close to me. I was relatively young when my Great Grandmother died, and of course I was upset, and of course I cried, but it was nothing like what I can imagine losing a sibling would be like.<br /><br />I have a younger brother, and he drives me insane sometimes, but, God, if I ever lost him? I don't know what I would do.<br /><br />I cannot begin to imagine what Laurel must have been feeling. Her parents were divorced, she lost her sister, her mom left to California, her dad shut himself away, and she switched schools. She had no one to be there for her when she needed them. When she met her friends, I was so relieved for her because she would now have someone to talk to.<br /><br />I knew Laurel had gone through a lot, but I did not expect this to be a book about rape.<br /><br />At all.<br /><br />I was surprised, but it wasn't a bad surprised. I think it added to Laurel's characters while not taking over the book. It was not primarily about this, but it was a huge thing that she needed to come to terms with. It was not described in detail, and we know a very limited amount about it, but we know it happened. And we know Laurel blames herself for it, which is one of the saddest things imaginable.<br /><br />Everything added to this book just made it better, and it kept building on itself, up and up and up, until it reached the final letter and concluded Laurel's story.<br /><br /><blockquote>People can leave, and then they can come back. It sounds simple, like an obvious thing. But when I realized that, the truth of it seemed important.</blockquote><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><b>Characters:</b><br /><br /><i>Laurel -</i><br />The main character, narrator, writer. I talked a lot about who she is above, but a little more can't hurt.<br />Laurel is such a sweet kid. We're not that far apart in age, and some of the things that happen to her, I can't imagine being in that position. In just one year, she faces what I hope I will <i>never</i> have to, and she still manages to be so strong. She cries, she mourns, she yells, but she is, after all, a normal teenager.<br />Laurel is so strong, and even though she was not my favorite main character ever, I admire her strength.<br /><br /><i>May -</i><br />Everything we learn about May is through Laurel's memories, so maybe they are candy coated and better than in reality, but May seems so amazing and insightful. We learn some things through others about May. She's not perfect after all. But she's pretty dang close.<br /><blockquote>"The universe is bigger than anything that can fit into your mind."</blockquote><br /><i>Dad -</i><br />In the beginning, he is like a hermit, but as the book goes on, he really opens up to Laurel and her friends, and I grew to like him a lot. He played wiffle ball with Sky and Laurel even though it was late, and he watched movies with Hannah and made his "famous enchiladas" for them. He really is a good dad, but he is so stricken with the grief of losing May and his wife that he does not know how to handle it.<br /><br /><i>Aunt Amy -</i><br />There is not much to say about Aunt Amy except that she loves <i>Mister Ed</i>, is a hopeless romantic, and worships Jesus like it's going out of style. She is way too good for the Jesus Man, as Laurel nicknames her "boyfriend", but I still didn't like her at first. When Laurel opened up to her, she opened up to Laurel, and she grew on me.<br /><br /><i>Sky -</i><br />Sky is the classic bad boy in the books. He wears the leather jacket and hangs out alone, but he has a soft side and cares for his mom so much. His dad left when he was young and his mom is a little loopy, but he loves her and rarely leaves her. He is Laurel's first love, and she is his, also.<br />BUT<br />he went to that Francesca girl and that was insanely idiotic of him because him and Laurel were perfect together, but he had that whole backstory saying, "It's how I cope. I don't have amazing friends like you. Blah blah blah."<br />THAT'S NO EXCUSE, SKYLAR.<br />Then he was back and all was well.<br /><br /><i>Natalie &amp; Hannah -</i><br />I would do them separately, but honestly, I can't come up with enough for each of them to do them both. So we'll do them as a package deal.<br />Natalie is so sweet and cool and she loves Hannah but that's all I have to say about that . . . so, you can see why I had to do this.<br />Hannah is a bit of a<i> - dare I say it?</i> No, I do not dare. But you'll get it when I'm done.<br />She dates, like, 5 guys at a time, and I'm 99.99% sure that she's hooking up with all of them, which is terrible because she's 15ish. You've got your whole life to lose it, girl, you don't need to rush. She does love Natalie, but she fights it because she is worried about what will happen when everyone finds out.<br />Now, I'm not going to state my position on that issue, because I don't want to offend anyone or anything, but my opinion on it did affect how I felt about Hannah and Natalie. Whether I liked them more when I found out or not, no one really needs to know. It's not necessary, so . . . yeah.<br />Ah, controversy.<br /><br /><i>Tristan -</i><br />Tristan has so much potential - as Kristen tells him all the time - to do whatever he would want. He has shown that he can get A's on papers and stuff, but he just doesn't try. He can play guitar really well, and I know he could start a band or something, and I hope he will. He can achieve so much if he just puts in the effort to succeed.<br />He is slowly killing himself with the negativity, and the failure, and the drugs, so he needs to get on track.<br />Well I like him anyway.<br />And he calls Laurel "Buttercup", which is adorable.<br /><br /><i>Kristen -</i><br />Kristen is the most down-to-earth character I think I have ever read about. She has long, flowing hair, and she wears long, flowing skirts, and she has a personality that not many possess. She is quiet, but it is because her words are bigger than she is. She is this small woman who hopes for so much, and I want so badly to see her stay with Tristan because she has changed him.<br />Things are getting deep over here in my head. Watch out. The inspirational thoughts are coming for you.<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><b>Overall:</b><br /><br />Even though I gave it 4 stars, <i>Love Letters to the Dead</i> is one of the most beautiful books I have ever read. It broke my heart and sewed it back together and then broke it again, just to glue them together AGAIN. It left me in pieces while also leaving me with life lessons and tears and memories of all the characters that I won't forget. I will remember this book for a long time.<br /><br />Thank you, Ava Dellaira.<br /><br /><br /><blockquote>If beauty is truth, and if truth is beauty, they are defined by each other, so how do we know the meaning of either? I think that we make our own meanings, by putting ourselves into them.</blockquote><br /><blockquote>Because I think that by beauty, you don't just mean something that's pretty. You mean something that makes us human.</blockquote></span>
  <a data-text-id="16871417291164935484" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


