    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_950540176" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/950540176" />
    <a title="J.m. Darhower" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1400656-j-m-darhower"><img alt="J.m. Darhower" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1456272468p2/1400656.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/950540176?book_show_action=true">May 28, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J.m. Darhower" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J.m. Darhower" href="/user/show/1400656-j-m-darhower">J.m. Darhower</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer950540176" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8929087431801604725">Love Letters to the Dead is the type of book you either love or hate. There&apos;s very little middle ground. Either you find it utterly brilliant, or you have a hard time even making it through the damn thing. And I can see why some might not like it... it&apos;s certainly not for everyone. I stayed up all night reading the book. Literally. All night. I finished the last word 45 minutes before my alarm went off.<br/><br/>And I don&apos;t regret it for a second.<br/><br/>I was awestruck by the author&apos;s bravery in tackling the sub</span>
  <span id="freeText8929087431801604725" style="display:none">Love Letters to the Dead is the type of book you either love or hate. There's very little middle ground. Either you find it utterly brilliant, or you have a hard time even making it through the damn thing. And I can see why some might not like it... it's certainly not for everyone. I stayed up all night reading the book. Literally. All night. I finished the last word 45 minutes before my alarm went off.<br /><br />And I don't regret it for a second.<br /><br />I was awestruck by the author's bravery in tackling the subjects it did in the format it did. Every single word is written in the form of a letter to a dead celebrity/writer/poet/whatnot. Sure, I could nitpick things, like how realistically it makes no sense that she'd write some of that to some of those celebrities (like the heavy dialogue scenes) BUT this is fiction, and the beauty of it is suspending disbelief. Would a teenager really write some of that? No. Did that matter a smidgen to me? Nope.<br /><br />I was left absolutely awestruck after finishing this story. I cried. I found it moving, and heartbreaking, and uplifting, so beautiful yet tragic at the same time. It's not an easy, light, fluffy read by any means. It will tear you apart at times. However, there are moments tucked in that truly give it soul, flashes of humor that I absolutely loved. Laurel's friends are amazing. Yes, some of the drama is a bit melodramatic, but come on... they're freaking high school kids, most of which are freshman. Are you really surprised they have friendship drama and guy issues, etc? That's what made it so damn REAL to me. It was so vivid, and rich, and that's so surprising given a lot of the book is telling vs. showing because of the letter format (I know, as a writing, telling more than showing is in general a no-no, but the way the author does it here is no short of genius in my opinion). I feel like I know these characters now, like they're real, and I mourn with them. I love with them. I'm thankful to have met them.<br /><br />Do I recommend this book? Abso-freakin-lutely. Will you like it? Maybe. Maybe not. It's a toss up. But it's absolutely worth giving it a try.<br /><br />I already want to re-read it.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8929087431801604725" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


